<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n56125b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n56" href="#n56125b">N56 (VI.B.41)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n56all.htm#n56125b"> 125(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> egli conquisto poi / la Scozia, e funne / re coronato <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n56125b"><li>FW 367.02 </li><li><a href="../../flex/mf/lexmf.htm#n56125b">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/mf/l39mf.htm#n56125b">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n56125b">MS BL 47480.231v</ms> </li><li>JJA 55:402 <a name="mfd5" href="../../ff/fdra/mda.htm#mfd5">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/mf/mfd5.htm#n56125b">Draft: II.3&sect;6.5</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Place this by the side of Boccaccio&apos;s favourite formulae: <mark>Egli conquist&ograve; poi la Scozia, e funne re coronato</mark> (ii, 3); Et onorevolmente visse infino alia fine (ii, 4); Molte volte goderono del loro amore: Iddio faccia noi goder del nostro (iii, 6): E cosi nella sua grossezza si rimase e ancor vi si sta (vi, 8). We have further docked this tail into: &ldquo;And they lived happily ever after.&rdquo; <small> Richard F. Burton, &ldquo;Terminal Essay&rdquo;, <a name="RBTE4" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#RBTE4"><cite title="source">The Book of the Thousand Nights and a Night</cite></a> (n.d.) X, 163</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Burton is quoting from <cite>The Decameron</cite> of Giovanni Boccaccio (private printing for The Villon Society, London, 1886), translated by his student John Payne (who also, with Burton&apos;s advice) translated the <cite>Thousand Nights and A Night</cite>. In this text, the tales each has its own style of concluding. The last words of II.3 are &ldquo;egli conquist&ograve; poi la Scozia, e funne Re coronato:&rdquo; = he after conquered Scotland and was crowned King thereof. Joyce notes the different endings at 357.29: &ldquo;howdifferend with ...&rdquo;. </mm> </dd></dl>
